    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1115
    old "As far as you can tell, there’s more than a dozen kids playing in the village, almost all of them on the western bank, and a slightly smaller group of teenagers, working together with adults in the east. They don’t seem to struggle with hunger, and the rugged clothes they’re wearing are appropriate for the weather. \n\nAs in most villages of The Dragonwoods, the younger kids are supervised by the elders, not necessarily those related to them. Their only duties involve learning the most basic of chores and staying out of trouble, which also means they rarely leave the village walls, and never without adults. \n\nThis carefree life ends for those who reach their tenth birthday, or even sooner. That’s when they start spending longer and longer hours experimenting with different types of labor, which leads to them being assigned a new trade. Once the new path is selected for them - with or without their consent - the days of play are over. "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1130
    old "Wandering down the alleys you find about ten elders, most of them on the western bank, where they take care of the children - overseeing the ones who can play on their own, and carrying the infants with them. A few of them also help with other chores - cooking, cleaning, or embroidering. \n\nIf there are any other elderly around, they are already tied to their houses, or even beds. "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1144
    old "You find a few people who struggle with wounded or weakened shells, yet spend their time outside, either laboring for the common good, or, if they are too impaired, avoiding boredom. \n\nThere’s one feature that marks almost all of the adults, especially the older ones - their hands are a bit stiff, marked by hundreds of cuts made with fish bones and knives, and burnt by the salt used in dressing fish. "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1159
    old "You find humble gardens and vegetable fields in both halves of the village. The farmers explain that these plants are but a small addition to their regular meals - the village would struggle without trading fish for regular crops and flour. "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1177
    old "You ask at the gate if there’s an option to travel either downstream or upstream. You’re told that there’s little purpose in doing so - the river starts in the wilderness, runs through a few sharp waterfalls, and ends in the salty waters. “Right, it’s merely used for one thing. Helps the fishers move the barrels down to the beach and back, but it still takes a few strong muscles.” "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1190
    old "It turns out that the foragers spend their time mostly by assisting the lumberjacks. There isn’t much food in the hills - small critters, eggs, berries, and green leaves, but in the woods the situation isn’t much better. "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1203
    old "You’re told that these rocky lands won’t support anything taller than a bush, or even a meadow. Aside from a few humble groves, which are best left to themselves, the village has no {i}forest garden{/i} at its disposal. "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1217
    old "You’re told that the guards offer no escort to travelers. “The roads went to shit, they did,” tells one of them. “When we leave, we do so in numbers big enough to fight off a troll. There’s no coin worth losing a neighbor.” "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1230
    old "You’re told that the potters only work once every year or two, when enough of the earthenware pots and cups break from use. "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1243
    old "Your questions are met with scowls and resentful remarks. “How can you even suggest such a thing?” "
