    old "A young carrier chuckles. “And what would you buy? Without a wagon, and donkeys? We sell barrels of fish, sacks of salt. When a caravan comes, we empty a warehouse, then fill it up again with food.” \n\nWhen you ask her if she’s sure there’s nothing useful that a lone traveler could get in such a large village, she seems a bit embarrassed. “Well... We have a weaponsmith, but he doesn’t sell any blades to outsiders. But... Maybe {color=#f6d6bd}Rufina{/color}, the tailor?” "
    new ""

    # game/areas/galerocks01structure.rpy:1561
    old "While fish are being smoked at any fireplace you find, the dedicated smokehouse is at the edge of the village, close to the saltery, but far enough to save the locals from some of its smell. You exchange a few words with the workers, learning that salting takes place mainly during night time, after the fresh fish arrive, and the smoking occurs all day long, “above torched shavings,” without much supervision. “Smoked fish stay fresh for longer than you think, unless you take them outside. Then the rotting starts after merely a few days, so we only sell them to the closer villages. Salted fish last for seasons, but you have to rinse them rightly in a stream, or they’ll burn your mouth with all them salt.” \n\nAs you observe the workers, most of whom seem either old, tiny, or hindered by past wounds, you notice how stiff their fingers seem to be, covered with cuts, making you wonder how much salt gets into even the slightest of scratches. Yet they talk with ease, spending most of their hours gathered in the square, chatting face to face without care, saying not a word about the smell and sight of the scaled, gutted, and boned creatures that surround them. \n\nYou ask about the prices of their barrels of fish and the way they are transported, learning that flour and other supplies are worth more to the locals than dragon bones. After a few minutes, you exchange goodbyes, trying to memorize the details useful for the city guild. While there are always fresh fish available in {color=#f6d6bd}Hovlavan{/color}, having a secure supply of preserved meat would be worth many coins during stormy or frozen days. "
    new ""

